      <description>&lt;div&gt;Just a couple concepts for the paladin class.  Compared to warriors and shadow knights, paladins take damage very poorly compared to other classes when you add everything up.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;1.  Warriors naturally mitigate better&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;2.  Shadowknights life tap to DPS, heal themselves, and agro the mob they are tanking (very efficient)&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The way a paladin decreases the ammount of damage it takes in any way above innate skill, is to stun a mob.  There is very  little a level 70 paladin in anguish or greater can stun either on raids or xp groups.  An SK can still tap a level 73 mob; a warrior doesn't lose mitigation when the mob is above level 70.  The only other way a paladin takes comparatively less damage is by targetting him or herself and healing.  While this is happeneing, the paladin is doing slim to no damage to the mob (damage shield and ripostes) and they are generating very little agro to hold the mob.  To sum it up, with mobs above level 70, paladins lose our balance of being a tank and get easily surpassed by the other two tank classes.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;My reccomendation would be to make just one of our 4 second stuns (with 1 sec cast) be able to affect mobs up to 5 levels higher than us (with the exclusing of raid mobs, which would be flagged stun immune).  This would provide us the equivalent ease of healing to that of an equally geared SK.  Yes we would still have our heals which SKs dont, but SKs still have the ability to pull with FD, do group mana, and to do appx twice our DPS on non undead mobs.  Overall I feel this proposition is ballanced and fair.  Thank you for any consideration.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;My second idea:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;I would liek to see Silent Piety revisited.  It originally had the DI component which was deemed to be overpowered.  IF the DI component was placed in there in the first place, I am assuming developers were not opposed to the idea, but didn't seem to see a way to ballance it.  I feel tying the DI component to our Lay Hands would work beautifully.  If a paladin has Silent Piety up and dies, or gets below X percent  (preferably 5 or lower since Lay hands is a decently long refresh), then the game does a check on Lay Hands.  If the ability is available, perform lay hands, and now lay hands is down and Silent Piety wears off.  Now if Silent Piety is cast again, there is no chance of a DI save until Lay Hands refreshes. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;I feel this would breathe life into this spell that is currently shunned by the pladin community, allow for the implementation of a concept developers already liked to some extent, and would not be overpowered or out of ballance since Lay Hands is an ability we have had since day one.  Thank you again for any consideration.&lt;/div&gt;</description>
